menu "breadboard: bb_ota_boot"

config BB_OTA_BOOT_PROGRESS_HTTP
    bool "Serve /api/update/progress + advertise mDNS during boot-mode OTA"
    default n
    help
      When set, bb_ota_boot stands up a one-route HTTP server (GET
      /api/update/progress) and advertises (responder-only, no browse) mDNS
      during the boot-mode OTA download, so a remote dashboard sees live
      progress and the device stays discoverable. Costs ~12 KB heap during
      the download (httpd task + mDNS responder). Leave off for heap-tight or
      headless consumers — the existing progress callback is unaffected.

      The transient GET /api/update/progress endpoint is ONLY available during
      the boot-mode OTA download window — it is not part of the normal-operation
      OpenAPI spec (boot-mode boards do not compile bb_ota_pull, so /progress
      is absent in normal mode). The response schema is identical to bb_ota_pull's
      /api/update/progress: {state:string, in_progress:bool, progress_pct:integer}.

config BB_OTA_BOOT_STATUS_HTTP
    bool "Serve GET /api/update/status + POST /api/update/check for boot-mode boards"
    default n
    help
      When set, bb_ota_boot registers two runtime routes on the main httpd
      (the normal registry path, not the transient boot-progress server):

        GET  /api/update/status  — returns cached bb_ota_check status JSON
                                   (same shape as the persistent worker route).
        POST /api/update/check   — on-demand one-shot manifest check. Guards
                                   against low heap: if the largest contiguous
                                   internal block is below the TLS threshold
                                   (auto-derived from
                                   CONFIG_MBEDTLS_SSL_IN_CONTENT_LEN + ~1 KB,
                                   or overridden by
                                   CONFIG_BB_TLS_HEAP_CONTIGUOUS_FLOOR) it
                                   returns 503 {"error":"insufficient_heap"}
                                   and leaves the cached result intact.
                                   Otherwise spawns a transient fat-stack task
                                   that calls bb_ota_check_now() then exits;
                                   responds 202 {"status":"checking"}
                                   immediately. Client polls
                                   GET /api/update/status for results.

      Intended for boot-strategy boards (e.g. ESP32-S2) that skip the
      persistent bb_ota_check worker (CONFIG_BB_OTA_CHECK_AUTOREGISTER
      defaults off for BB_OTA_STRATEGY_BOOT) but still need a runtime status
      endpoint for the web UI and taipan-cli. bb_ota_check is initialised
      once at startup using the releases_url/board values passed to
      bb_ota_boot_run_if_pending; if that function has not been called yet the
      routes respond with 503.

      No persistent worker task is created — the only TLS activity is on-demand
      via POST /api/update/check, and only when heap permits.

config BB_OTA_CHECK_ON_APPLY_FALLBACK
    bool "Return check_on_apply directive instead of insufficient_heap"
    depends on BB_OTA_BOOT_STATUS_HTTP
    default n
    help
      When POST /api/update/check cannot allocate the contiguous heap the TLS
      manifest fetch needs, return 200 {"status":"check_on_apply"} (and mark
      GET /api/update/status outcome=check_on_apply, available=false) instead
      of 503 {"error":"insufficient_heap"}. Signals API consumers to skip the
      runtime check and POST /api/update/apply directly — boot-mode performs
      the manifest check at full early-boot heap. Opt-in; off preserves the
      insufficient_heap error.

endmenu
